desire and resisted none. Pollak suggests that this goal remains imperfectly achieved in his writings, which liberates some forbidden voices and silences others. Integrating biography and criticism, Pollak employs a loosely chronological organization to describe the poet's multifaceted "faith in sex." Drawing on his early fiction, journalism, poetry, and self-reviews, as well as letters and notebook entries, she shows how in spite of his personal ambivalence about sustained erotic intimacy, Whitman came to imagine himself as "the phallic choice of America."  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aErotic poetry, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality and literaturexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMale homosexuality in literature. 0aSex in literature. 4aAmerican. 4aGeneral. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aPollak, Vivian R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022190140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092430740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924307423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924307/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles